    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "From the perspective of the Fraud Triangle, which factor represents the environmental condition that most contributes to the occurrence of fraud?",
      "tag": "Opportunity",
      "options": [
        "A. Employee dissatisfaction with compensation",
        "B. Deficiencies in the organization's internal controls",
        "C. High personal indebtedness of the perpetrator",
        "D. Absence of formal training programs"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Deficient or nonexistent internal controls create the opportunity necessary for fraud to be perpetrated, representing the most relevant environmental factor. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual 2024)",
      "justification_wrong": "Dissatisfaction and indebtedness are pressure elements; absence of training is an organizational factor, not the opportunity element of the triangle.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "fraud_investigation/quiz_002_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "Among the motivational factors of the Fraud Triangle, which pressure factor shows the highest recurrence in documented cases?",
      "tag": "Pressure",
      "options": [
        "A. Greed disconnected from concrete necessity",
        "B. Financial pressure resulting from debt or lifestyle demands",
        "C. Mere availability of opportunity",
        "D. Desire for retaliation against the organization"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Financial pressure—debts, lifestyle incompatible with income, or gambling losses—is the most frequently identified motivator in occupational fraud cases. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual 2024)",
      "justification_wrong": "Greed, opportunity, and retaliation may motivate frauds, but financial pressure is the predominant factor in ACFE studies.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "fraud_investigation/quiz_002_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "In the Fraud Diamond model, capability refers to which attribute of the individual?",
      "tag": "Fraud Diamond",
      "options": [
        "A. The financial pressure that motivates fraudulent action",
        "B. The competencies, authority, and trust to exploit an opportunity",
        "C. The rationalization that internally justifies the conduct",
        "D. The physical or logical access to organizational resources"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Capability in the Fraud Diamond encompasses personal traits, hierarchical position, intelligence, and authority that enable an individual not only to commit fraud but also to conceal it effectively.",
      "justification_wrong": "Financial pressure is the 'pressure' element; rationalization is the 'rationalization' element of the Fraud Triangle; physical access is part of 'opportunity' — capability is the personal and positional enabler.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "law_cfe/quiz_002_en.json"
    },
