    {
      "id": "S3D01-Q011",
      "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior",
      "question": "Which of the following best describes the concept of 'moral disengagement' in the context of occupational fraud?",
      "options": [
        "The process by which individuals convince themselves that ethical standards do not apply to them in particular contexts, allowing them to commit fraud without feeling guilty",
        "The organizational policy that separates personal morals from business decisions to maximize profitability",
        "The psychological state where an employee becomes completely detached from workplace relationships",
        "The legal defense strategy that argues the accused was unaware of moral implications of their actions"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 0,
      "explanation": "Moral disengagement refers to the cognitive process by which individuals selectively disengage their moral self-sanctions, allowing them to engage in unethical behavior without experiencing distress or guilt. In fraud contexts, perpetrators use mechanisms such as moral justification, euphemistic labeling, advantageous comparison, displacement of responsibility, diffusion of responsibility, distortion of consequences, dehumanization, and attribution of blame to psychologically reconstruct their harmful conduct as acceptable. This differs from rationalization in the Fraud Triangle as it represents a broader psychological framework explaining how people suspend their moral standards. Understanding moral disengagement helps fraud examiners recognize warning signs and develop more effective prevention strategies by addressing the cognitive mechanisms that enable fraudulent behavior.",
